102.m_mText:
"'Thank you, Dr. Ressa.'
The elderly woman before me bowed repeatedly in her gratitude.
Though I've lost count of how many patients I've treated today, her smile still gave me a glimmer of strength.
For years, I've done my utmost to help these patients in remote villages.
'Why do you go to such lengths, Dr. Ressa?' the old woman asked before she left.
Why indeed...
Is it because of the horrors of war I've experienced, and the fear of death they instilled in me?
Or is it guilt over the lives taken, driving me to cherish it above all else?
I do not know. But now, all I want is to keep everyone as far from death as possible, no matter the toll it takes on me—
After all, only this makes me feel truly alive."

104.m_mText: "Friedrich first met Gilrain Cidhall when their families brought them to the Church. Initially, Friedrich was wary of Gilrain, doubting his integrity. Despite this, they were assigned together to improve relations between their families, which led to some awkward interactions. However, as they served together as soldiers and fought side by side, their mutual distrust gradually softened into a genuine friendship. By the time they were both selected as candidates for the role of the Bell Ringer of Light, their bond had grown strong enough that they trusted each other completely in battle."

101.m_mText:
"Nicole Flamel was a renowned ballerina from East Boulevard, but during the infamous 'Libation Day' siege, her legs became trapped under a collapsed building. She was rescued in time, but her mangled legs had to be amputated. Unable to ever dance again, Flamel became increasingly depressed. Yet on the brink of despair, she encountered Albrecht the Crystal Sage, a Bell Ringer who told her he could let her dance again. Flamel regained her hope and voluntarily became Albrecht's test subject, as well as his apprentice.
She felt grateful towards her mentor, but their master-apprentice relationship revealed to her Albrecht's contempt for the world.
'I've seen your dance. It's beautiful and shouldn't be taken from this world, even if the world itself shall disappear.'
Though unable to agree with his stance, Flamel nonetheless carried out bounty missions for Albrecht as a way of repayment."

104.m_mText:
"At some point, I became known as the accomplice of demons. Despite being a healer, people avoided me wherever I went, their eyes filled with fear.
'Raven Mask Demon'—that's what they called me. When I asked my colleagues why, they could only offer resigned looks:
'You always use the sacrifice of some to save others.'
Was that so wrong?
I've never understood why it was considered a mistake to let some die to ensure the survival of many others. I pondered this question in the lab, my vision blurring, my body heating, my limbs growing weak...
'Ahem—'
Was the dark red blood on the desk really from my own body?
It turned out I had been infected by the patients without even realizing it.
Should I also lock myself away and prevent others from getting infected?"

101.m_mText:
"Humans are food.
That was the first thing my sister told me when I arrived in the territory. Her voice was unfeeling, as I stood at the edge of the bustling crowd.
They looked like me. Moved like me. I couldn't understand how she saw them as nothing more than prey.
But then a girl approached. She carried flowers and a scent—not of petals, but something irresistible.
It struck a chord somewhere primal. My doubts trembled.
'Can you feel it? This is food.'
Then my sister placed the little girl's hand into mine, her crimson eyes shimmering with ravenous hunger.
Perhaps it was an invitation—to blood. She handed me a dagger, the Bathory crest gleaming on it. 'She is yours now.'
And just like that, she vanished, leaving me alone with the girl. The girl held out a flower. 'Lord asked me to give you these.'
'Why?'
'It's for your birthday... You must really love flowers, miss?'
Do I? I don't know.
But at that moment, the fragrance of blossoms masked the thirst in my chest..."

"PH-Mouret, a town in the northwest of The Howling Peninsula, is part of the Ganelon family. Recent cases of suspected Black Blood disease have emerged, and all former Gravekeepers have vanished after leaving their posts, prompting a secret investigation. 
Investigation revealed that local water has been contaminated. The source is the <style=Highlight>'Child of the Plague', Sheila the Firstborn, who was watched by the Ganelon family for generations.</style>
The cause of the previous Gravekeeper disappearances remains unclear. The current Gravekeeper, Clive, shows signs of beast transformation and is suspected to working with the Child of the Plague to accelerate the spread of the Black Blood disease. 
The Black Blood disease is a divine punishment from Aeon. Carriers gradually lose their sanity and become uncontrollably violent. <style=Highlight>If left unchecked, no pure land will remain in Minexus. Thus, Thibault, Bell Ringer No. ⅩⅠ, has ordered the purge of Mouret. May Aeon's gospel heal this land tainted by the Black Blood.</style>
—Tempus Church Investigation Manuscript Ⅰ 

An undocumented outbreak has occurred in a northern village affiliated with Bathory. 
Investigation revealed that <style=Highlight>Hati the Secondborn, also known as 'Plague's Origin,' </style> passed through the area and caused an illness through scales. She has been added to the pursuit list. 
—Tempus Church Investigation Manuscript Ⅱ"
